y":"当Matilda Boteler or Butler于1199年出生在英国可瓦爾时，她的父亲William Butler60岁，母亲Matilda de Teynham27岁。她于大约1219年与Edward de Godolphin I结婚。他们至少是1个儿子的父母。"},"hr":{"1199–Deceased":"1199.–preminula","1199–Female":"1199.–preminula","1195–1225":"1195–1225","1220–1269":"1220–1269","1140–Male":"1140–preminuo","1173–Female":"1173–preminula","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1269":"1269","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1199":"1199.","1220":"1220","1173":"1173","1140":"1140","1195":"1195","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England"},"cs":{"1199–Deceased":"1199–Zesnulá","1199–Female":"1199–Zesnulá","1195–1225":"1195–1225","1220–1269":"1220–1269","1140–Male":"1140–Zesnulý","1173–Female":"1173–Zesnulá","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1269":"1269","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1199":"1199","1220":"1220","1173":"1173","1140":"1140","1195":"1195","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, Anglie"},"da":{"1199–Deceased":"1199–Afdød","1199–Female":"1199–Afdød","1195–1225":"1195–1225","1220–1269":"1220–1269","1140–Male":"1140–Afdød","1173–Female":"1173–Afdød","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1269":"1269","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1199":"1199","1220":"1220","1173":"1173","1140":"1140","1195":"1195","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England"},"nl":{"1199–Deceased":"1199–Overleden","1199–Female":"1199–Overleden","1195–1225":"1195–1225","1220–1269":"1220–1269","1140–Male":"1140–Overleden","1173–Female":"1173–Overleden","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1269":"1269","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1199":"1199","1220":"1220","1173":"1173","1140":"1140","1195":"1195","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England"},"en":{"1199–Deceased":"1199–Deceased","1199–Female":"1199–Deceased","1195–1225":"1195–1225","1220–1269":"1220–1269","1140–Male":"1140–Deceased","1173–Female":"1173–Deceased","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1269":"1269","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1199":"1199","1220":"1220","1173":"1173","1140":"1140","1195":"1195","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Boteler","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name for a maker of leather bottles, from an agent derivative of Middle English <i>botel</i>, Old French <i>bouteille</i> ‘bottle’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"or","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Jewish (Israeli): from Hebrew <i>or</i> ‘light’, a Hebraicized form of various original Ashkenazic surnames.","Chinese: Cantonese form of the surname 柯, see   Ke   1.","Chinese: Hokkien form of the surname 胡, see   Hu   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Ke","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Heng, Yong, Bin, Song, Yan, Zhi, Cheng, Chih-Ming, Chun-Yen, Fan, Fong, Gang.  Vietnamese Lan, Hai, Hoa, Le Van, Mui, Tuy.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 柯, meaning ‘bough, stalk’ in Chinese: (i) from the first element of the personal name Ke Lu (柯盧), personal name of a prince of the state of Wu during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (ii) from the first element of the placename Ke Ze (柯澤), the name of a fief (located in Shandong province) granted to an official in the state of Qi during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (iii) traced back to the Qiang ethnic group in ancient western China and the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China. (iv) adopted as a surname by the Ke Ba (柯拔) family from the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ).","Chinese: variant of   Ge  ."]}]},{"name":"Butler","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from a word that originally denoted a wine steward, usually the chief servant of a medieval household, from Norman French <i>butuiller</i> (Old French <i>bouteillier</i>, Latin <i>buticularius</i>, from <i>buticula</i> ‘bottle’). In the large households of royalty and the most powerful nobility, the title came to denote an officer of high rank and responsibility, only nominally concerned with the supply of wine, if at all. As well as being widespread in England, this is also the surname of an important Irish family, descended from Theobald FitzWalter, who was appointed Chief Butler of Ireland by King Henry II in 1177. It is Gaelicized as <i>de Buitléir</i>.","English: occasionally perhaps an occupational name from Middle English <i>boteler</i> ‘maker of bottles (usually of leather)’, a derivative of Middle English <i>botel</i>, Old French <i>bo(u)teille</i> ‘bottle’ and synonymous with <i>Botelmaker</i>.","Americanized form of French   Bouthillier   (see   Bouteiller  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Buttler","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Butler  .","German: occupational name for a village tavern owner, from French <i>bouteillier</i> ‘butler’.","Americanized form of German <b>Buttlar</b>: habitational name from a place so named in Thuringia."]},{"name":"Bouthillier","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Armand, Jacques, Normand, Philippe, Yves.","French: variant of   Bouteiller  . This name is sometimes Americanized as   Butler  . Compare   Boutilier  ."]}]},{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Old German: Mighty battle maid"]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":16,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":25,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705189,"age":60,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Matilda Boteler or Butler was born in 1199, in Cornwall, England, her father, William Butler, was 60 and her mother, Matilda de Teynham, was 27. She married Edward de Godolphin I about 1219. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"1199–Deceased":"1199–Surnud","1199–Female":"1199–Surnud","1195–1225":"1195–1225","1220–1269":"1220–1269","1140–Male":"1140–Surnud","1173–Female":"1173–Surnud","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1269":"1269","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1199":"1199","1220":"1220","1173":"1173","1140":"1140","1195":"1195","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England"},"fi":{"1199–Deceased":"1199–Kuollut","1199–Female":"1199–Kuollut","1195–1225":"1195–1225","1220–1269":"1220–1269","1140–Male":"1140–Kuollut","1173–Female":"1173–Kuollut","1259":"1259","